Our baseline for survival rate is 0.38, that is the “no information” chance of survival. Lets take a look at the what seems to be the categorical variables:

It looks we need the “name”, “sex” and “cabin” features in order to extract any meaninful information from it.

Cleaning Name feature

What feature in the name may be an indicator for survival? Let’s take a look

train_data[,head(name)]

[1] "Braund, Mr. Owen Harris"                             "Cumings, Mrs. John Bradley (Florence Briggs Thayer)"
[3] "Heikkinen, Miss. Laina"                              "Futrelle, Mrs. Jacques Heath (Lily May Peel)"       
[5] "Allen, Mr. William Henry"                            "Moran, Mr. James"

Our first hypothesis: either alias (a well known subject) or its title is an indication for greater survival rate. Lets extract those and try to correlate with the survival rate.

Defining new features from name

Correlation with survival

The top 6 titles, may constitute our base category, we leaver the remaining as the “other” category

Its seem our assumptions were correct, those with nickname or a distinctive title have a greater survival rate than those who don’t.

Let’s build a random forest model with cross-validation and perform an extensive gridsearch.

# train model

tunegrid <- expand.grid(.mtry=c(seq(1,10,3)), .ntree=c(100,400,900))

seed=814
set.seed(seed)
registerDoMC(cores=7)

                          size=-1/log(Accuracy),

The lda model seems to be less overfitted than the RF model, the performances of both models are quite similar on the validation set. We observe a significant drop in the predicted survival probability between survivors and desceased. Instead of predicting the number of survivors, the output of the model is a ranked list of passengers from the most probable to survive to the least. The expected number of survivors depends on the number of boats available.

Beyond the 150th top passenger the survival probability drops significantly.
